\begin{document}

\title{Introduction: The giant dipole resonance}

\author{\gnm{J{\"o}rn} \fnm{Kleemann}\inst{1",ORC="https://orcid.org/0000-0003-2596-3762}\contact{jkleemann@ikp.tu-darmstadt.de}}

\institute{<OrgID Level="Institution" Type="GRID">grid.6546.1</OrgID>\orgdiv{Technical University of Darmstadt, Department of Physics}\orgname{Institute for Nuclear Physics}\orgadd{\city{Darmstadt}\country{Germany}}}

\maketitle


\label{ch:Introduction}
\IMRADlabel{introduction}

\section[Overview of the GDR and its importance]{Overview of the giant dipole resonance and its importance}
The photoresponse of atomic nuclei is an elementary aspect of nuclear physics and plays a crucial role in many areas of research, basic and applied, ranging from nuclear structure and astrophysics to reactor design, nuclear non-proliferation and medical-isotope production~\cite{Zilges2022-NRF-Review, Kneissl1996-NRF-Review, Goriely2019-PSF-Database, Tamii2023, Wiedeking2024-PSF-For-Nucleosynthesis, Baldo2016-Photoabsorption-For-Symmety-Energy, Bertozzi2005-NRF-Imaging-Application, Pruet2006-NRF-Imaging-Application, Hayakawa2010-NRF-Imaging-Application, Habs2011-Medical-Radioisotopes,Luo2016-Medical-Radioisotopes}.
As illustrated in \cref{fig:E1-Strength-Distribution-Sketch}, it is dominated by the isovector giant dipole resonance (GDR), a collective, $\Pi L$ ($\Pi L$) excitation of the nucleus, which involves all its nucleons~\cite{Harakeh2001-Book}.
In the macroscopic geometrical model, the isovector giant dipole resonance (GDR) corresponds to an out-of-phase oscillation of the protons against the neutrons, while microscopically it is regarded as a collective one-particle-one-hole (1p-1h) excitation built on the ground state~\cite{SpethWambach1991-GDR-Theory,Speth1981-GDR-Review,Harakeh2001-Book}.
The \gls{gdr} is inherent to all nuclei, except the very lightest~\cite{Harakeh2001-Book}, which, together with its reign over the electric dipole response, makes it one of the most fundamental nuclear excitations, if not the most.
As such, it allows to probe the elementary structure and dynamics of the complex many-body systems of atomic nuclei and, in particular, their bulk properties, such as shape and symmetry energy~\cite{Harakeh2001-Book}.
For this reason it also acts as an important benchmark for testing nuclear models and theories.

\begin{figure}[t]
  \includegraphics{figures/E1-Strength-Distribution-Sketch.pdf}
  \caption[Sketch of a typical nuclear electric dipole response]{
    Sketch of a typical electric dipole response expected for a heavy spherical nucleus~\cite{Harakeh2001-Book,Pietralla2024-NRF-Review}.
    %The electric dipole response is dominated by the \gls{gdr}, which also makes up the majority of the photoabsorption cross section of atomic nuclei in general.
    The electric dipole response constitutes the majority of the photoabsorption cross section of atomic nuclei and is itself dominated by the \gls{gdr}.
    As illustrated, the \gls{gdr}, located above the neutron separation threshold $S(\text{n})$, dwarfs all other excitations relevant to the nuclear photoresponse, such as the Pygmy Dipole Resonance~\cite{Savran2013-Pygmy-Review,Bracco2019-Pygmy-Review} and the two-phonon state~\cite{Zilges2022-NRF-Review,Kneissl2006-NRF-Review}.
  }
  \label{fig:E1-Strength-Distribution-Sketch}
\end{figure}

The excitation energy of the \gls{gdr} typically lies between \qtyrange{10}{30}{\MeV}~\cite{Harakeh2001-Book,BermanFultz1975-GDR-CS-Measurements-Review}, depending smoothly on the mass number of the nucleus, as typical for a collective excitation.
It usually appears as a pronounced Lorentzian peak in the photoabsorption cross section of spherical nuclei with widths of several \unit{\MeV}~\cite{BermanFultz1975-GDR-CS-Measurements-Review,DietrichBerman1988-GDR-CS-Measurements-Review}.
In heavy, deformed nuclei, a clear splitting of the \gls{gdr} into two overlapping Lorentzians is observed. %, as evident for \Sm in \cref{fig:GDR-Splitting-Evolution-Sm-Isotopes}.
The phenomenon is evident for \Sm in \cref{fig:GDR-Splitting-Evolution-Sm-Isotopes}.
% This phenomenon is apparent in \cref{fig:GDR-Splitting-Evolution-Sm-Isotopes}, which shows total photoneutron cross sections of samarium isotopes.
% evolution of the \gls{gdr} in the total photoneutron cross section of samarium isotopes is depicted.
\begin{figure}
  \includegraphics{figures/GDR-Splitting-Evolution-Sm-Isotopes.pdf}
  \caption[Evolution of the splitting of the GDR in samarium isotopes]{
    % $K$ splitting of the \gls{gdr} is clearly observed for the deformed \Sm, while the spherical \ce{^{144}Sm} shows a single Lorentzian resonance peak.
    Experimental total photoneutron cross sections of samarium isotopes.
    The $K$ splitting of the \gls{gdr} emerges as the deformation increases with mass number from the semi-magic, spherical \ce{^{144}Sm} to the well-deformed \Sm.
    The data, measured by \textcite{Carlos1974-GDR-CS-154Sm}, was retrieved from the EXFOR database~\cite{EXFOR,EXFOR-Interface} and has been offset in magnitude across the isotopes for better visibility.
  }
  \label{fig:GDR-Splitting-Evolution-Sm-Isotopes}
\end{figure}
This splitting is considered one of the prime signatures of nuclear deformation~\cite{Davidson1965-Rotations-Vibrations-Deformed-Review}.
It is easily understood in the geometrical model, where an axial deformation of the nucleus allows the oscillation of protons and neutrons against each other either along the nuclear symmetry axis or perpendicular to it~\cite{GoldhaberTeller1948-GDR-Hydrodynamic-Model,SteinwedelJensen1950-GDR-Hydrodynamic-Model,JensenJensen1950-GDR-Hydrodynamic-Model,SteinwedelJensenJensen1950-GDR-Hydrodynamic-Model}.
Since the axes have different lengths, the frequencies of the oscillations differ, and therefore, the \gls{gdr} splits into two peaks with a stronger splitting for stronger deformations~\cite{Danos1958-GDR-Splitting-Model,Okamoto1958-GDR-Splitting-Model}.
One commonly assigns $K$-quantum numbers\footnote{
  The $K$-quantum number gives the projection of the angular momentum $\vec{J}$ onto the symmetry axis of the nucleus.
  Consequently, it is only a good quantum number in the case of axially symmetric nuclei~\cite{DavydovFilippov1958-Triaxiality}.
} $K=0$ and $K=1$ to these two oscillation modes, reflecting the geometric interpretation of the distinct oscillation axes~\cite{Harakeh2001-Book}.
The $K=0$ mode corresponds to the oscillation along the symmetry axis, while the $K=1$ mode corresponds to the oscillation perpendicular to it.
Naturally, in triaxial nuclei, the \gls{gdr} is expected to split into three peaks, corresponding to the three possible oscillation modes along the three principal, now distinct, axes of the nucleus.
The photoabsorption cross section $\sigma_\text{Abs}$ is therefore usually parametrized by a sum of up to three standard Lorentzians (SLOs)~\cite{Harakeh2001-Book,BermanFultz1975-GDR-CS-Measurements-Review}, i.e.,
\begin{equation}\label{eq:GDR-Photoabsorption-Cross-Section-Parametrization}
  \sigma_\text{Abs}(E) = \sum_{k=1}^{3} \sigma^\text{SLO}_k(E) = \sum_{k=1}^{3} \frac{{\res{\sigma}}_k }{1+\left(\frac{E^2 - {\res{E}}_k^2}{E \Gamma_k}\right)^2} \eqComma
\end{equation}
where ${\res{E}}_k$, $\Gamma_k$ and ${\res{\sigma}}_k$ are the resonance energy, the full width at half maximum (FWHM) and the on-resonance photoabsorption cross section of the respective sub-resonances and $E$ the incident photon energy.
Due to the similar nature of the sub-resonances in the geometrical picture, it is expected that the energy-integrated photoabsorption cross sections
\begin{equation}
  \int \sigma^\text{SLO}_k(E) \dd E=\frac{\piC}{2} {\res{\sigma}}_k \Gamma_k
\end{equation}
of the three principal sub-resonances have similar magnitudes.
In axially deformed nuclei this leads to the expectation of a $2:1$ ratio of the $K=1$ and $K=0$ sub-resonances, which is indeed in rough agreement with experimental data~\cite{Harakeh2001-Book}.
% If it were possible to separate the sub-resonances, the \gls{gdr} would allow to probe otherwise hard to constrain triaxiality in nuclei. However from photoabsorption cross section data alone, this is not trivial.

A benchmark for the integrated photoabsorption cross section of a resonance is the Thomas-Reiche-Kuhn (TRK) sum rule~\cite{Thomas1925-TRK-Sum-Rule,Kuhn1925-TRK-Sum-Rule,ReicheThomas1925-TRK-Sum-Rule}.
The Thomas-Reiche-Kuhn (TRK) sum rule gives an idealized theoretical limit of the integrated $\Pi L$ ($\Pi L$) photoabsorption cross section of a nucleus with $Z$ protons and $N$ neutrons~\cite{Harakeh2001-Book,Speth1981-GDR-Review}.
It states
\begin{equation}
  \int_0^\infty \sigma^{\symup{E}1}_\text{Abs}(E) \dd E = \frac{2 \piC^2 \, \unit{\elementarycharge\squared} \, \hbar c}{4\piC \epsilon_0 \, m_\text{N} c^2}\frac{Z \, N}{N+Z} \approx 60 \frac{Z \, N}{N+Z}\,\unit{\MeV \milli\barn}
\end{equation}
in SI units, where $\sigma^{\symup{E}1}_\text{Abs}(E)$ is the \glsdisp{PiL}{$\symup{E}1$} photoabsorption cross section at photon energy $E$, $m_\text{N}$ is the average nucleon mass, and $\epsilon_0$ is the vacuum permittivity.
The \gls{gdr} usually exhausts \qty{100}{\percent} or more\footnote{
  The \gls{trk} sum rule underestimates the \glsdisp{PiL}{$\symup{E}1$} limit due to the omission of neutron-proton exchange contributions.
  To account for these, the sum rule is usually corrected by multiplying it by a factor of $(1+\kappa)$~\cite{Speth1981-GDR-Review}, where $\kappa$ is the so-called enhancement factor, which ranges from about \qtyrange{0}{30}{\percent} according to experimental data~\cite{BermanFultz1975-GDR-CS-Measurements-Review}.
} of this sum rule, which justifies its designation as a giant resonance.

Finally, due to its location above the particle separation thresholds, the \gls{gdr} is particle unbound and decays predominantly through particle emission~\cite{BermanFultz1975-GDR-CS-Measurements-Review}.
For medium and heavy nuclei neutron emission is by far the dominant decay channel due to their rather high Coulomb barriers.
Therefore, the photoabsorption cross section of the \gls{gdr} is commonly approximated by the total photoneutron cross section $\sigma_{\Sigma \text{n}}$ in these cases, i.e. by
\begin{equation}\label{eq:GDR-Photoabsorption-Cross-Section-Approximation}
  \sigma_\text{Abs}(E) \approx \sigma_{\Sigma \text{n}}(E) \coloneqq \sum_{k=1}^\infty \left(\sigma_{(\Î³,k\,\text{n})} + \sum_{X\neq\text{n}} \sigma_{(\Î³,k\,\text{n}+X)}\right)\eqComma
\end{equation}
where $X$ denotes any particle or combination of particles not including neutron (n).
In this approximation the contributions of any non-neutron-emitting photonuclear reactions to the photoabsorption cross section are neglected.
The photoabsorption cross section of the \gls{gdr} has been extensively studied in a vast number of experiments throughout the entire nuclear chart~\cite{BermanFultz1975-GDR-CS-Measurements-Review,DietrichBerman1988-GDR-CS-Measurements-Review}.
A majority of the data was obtained from photoneutron measurements using Real photon (real photon) beams and the approximation of \cref{eq:GDR-Photoabsorption-Cross-Section-Approximation}.

Still, the \gls{gdr} is known to also decay internally by \Î³ emission with a branching ratio of about \qty{1}{\percent}~\cite{Beene1990-GDR-208Pb-Gamma-Branching,Boretzky1996-GDR-208Pb-Gamma-Branching,Hass1971-GDR-NRF-ng-Source,BarNoyMoreh1974-GDR-NRF-ng-Source,Jackson1975-GDR-NRF-ng-Source,FullerHayward1962-GDR-NRF-Bremsstrahlung,NathanMoreh1980-GDR-NRF-Tagger,HoblitNathan1991-GDR-NRF-Tagger}.
Although the effect of this decay branch on the photoabsorption cross section may be small, its implications on the structure of the resonance are profound.
The \Î³-decay behavior is a fundamental aspect that provides a unique window into the internal structure of the \gls{gdr} and, therefore, also the nucleus as a whole.
In particular, the geometrical model of the \gls{gdr} makes explicit predictions about its \Î³-decay behavior to the $J^\piPar=\jp2+$ and \jp0+ members of the ground-state band~\cite{Baldin1960-GDR-NRF-Theory,Hayward1970-Book-Photonuclear-Reactions,MaricMoebius1959-GDR-NRF-CS-Theory,FullerHayward1962-GDR-NRF-Bremsstrahlung}.
These predictions are parameter-free with respect to a given photoabsorption cross-section parameterization and therefore provide an opportunity for a stringent test of the model, especially in the case of deformed nuclei, where its predictions are the most distinct and the model itself is the most regarded~\cite{Harakeh2001-Book}.
Yet, despite its importance and decades of research on the \gls{gdr}, the \Î³ decay is still scarcely studied.
Only a few experiments have been conducted to investigate it, paling in comparison to the vast number of photoneutron experiments.
Moreover, the few available measurements either cover only low \gls{gdr} excitation energies~\cite{Hass1971-GDR-NRF-ng-Source,BarNoyMoreh1974-GDR-NRF-ng-Source,Jackson1975-GDR-NRF-ng-Source} or suffer from insufficient resolution and statistics~\cite{FullerHayward1962-GDR-NRF-Bremsstrahlung,NathanMoreh1980-GDR-NRF-Tagger,HoblitNathan1991-GDR-NRF-Tagger}.
Thus, a comprehensive experimental assessment of the \Î³-decay behavior of the \gls{gdr} and its energy evolution is still missing.
In particular, for deformed nuclei, the evolution of the \Î³-decay branching ratios to the \st2+1 and \st0+1 states remains unmeasured, leaving the predictions by the geometrical model of the \gls{gdr} for these observables largely untested.
This is because until the recent advent of laser-Compton back-scattering (LCB) photon sources~\cite{Weller2009-HIGS,Howell2021-HIGS2-Workshop-Whitepaper,Weller2015-HIGS-NuclPhysNews,Hajima2016-LCS-Sources}, offering \unit{\MeV}-ranged photon beams with unprecedented intensity, polarization, and energy resolution, it has simply been impossible to efficiently excite the \gls{gdr} in narrow, freely selectable energy regions to study its \Î³ decay with high resolution and statistics.
To address this long-standing issue, it is the purpose of this work to pioneer a novel experimental approach to systematically study the \Î³ decay of the \gls{gdr} of both spherical and deformed nuclei, thereby launching a new experimental campaign in \gls{gdr} research using state-of-the-art laser-Compton back-scattering (LCB) photon sources.


\section[A brief history of the GDR]{A brief history of the giant dipole resonance}
The \gls{gdr} was already discovered in the early days of nuclear physics~\cite{BotheGentner1937,BaldwinKlaiber1947,BaldwinKlaiber1948} and has since continuously attracted a great deal of attention~\cite{Harakeh2001-Book,Speth1981-GDR-Review,BermanFultz1975-GDR-CS-Measurements-Review,DietrichBerman1988-GDR-CS-Measurements-Review,Bortignon2019-Book-Giant-Resonances-Finite-Temperature,Goriely2019-PSF-Database}.

First hints of the \gls{gdr} were found in 1937 by W.~Bothe and W.~Gentner~\cite{BotheGentner1937} when they studied nuclear transmutation induced by \qty{17}{\MeV} \Î³ rays for various samples.
Based on the strong variance they observed in the photodisintegration cross sections across different nuclei, they hypothesized that resonance phenomena might be involved in the process.

N.~Bohr further elaborated on this hypothesis in 1938~\cite{Bohr1938-GDR-Photoeffect}.
In particular, he showed that a resonance in the photoabsorption cross section is not in contradiction to the compound-nucleus model, which was widely used at the time to explain neutron-induced reactions.

In 1944 A.~Migdal published a hydrodynamical theory, which explicitly predicted the existence of a collective nuclear dipole resonance at energies above the neutron separation threshold~\cite{Migdal1944,IshkhanovKapitonov2021-GDR-History-Midgal}.
However, his work was not widely recognized at the time.

The first clear observation of the \gls{gdr} was reported by G.~C.~Baldwin and G.~S.~Klaiber in 1946~\cite{BaldwinKlaiber1947,BaldwinKlaiber1948}.
A new betatron electron accelerator enabled them to produce continuous Bremsstrahlung radiation with an endpoint energy up to \qty{100}{\MeV}.
With this tunable photon source, they measured the energy dependence of the cross sections of uranium and thorium photofission as well as \C and \ce{^{63}Cu} (\Î³,n) photodisintegration.
In all four cases, a similar resonance peak in the cross sections was observed with centroid energies ranging from about \qty{15}{\MeV} for uranium to \qty{30}{\MeV} for \C.

Unaware of Migdal's publication, M.~Goldhaber and E.~Teller~\cite{GoldhaberTeller1948-GDR-Hydrodynamic-Model} independently proposed a similar hydrodynamical model to explain this new resonance phenomenon shortly after, which was then regarded as the first theoretical explanation of the \gls{gdr}.
Assuming that the nucleus behaves like a macroscopic drop of proton and neutron fluids, the \gls{gdr} was interpreted as a collective isovector dipole oscillation of these two fluids against each other, resonantly excited by photoabsorption in the experiments by Baldwin and Klaiber.
In such a geometrical model, the \gls{gdr} must be a universal feature of all nuclei, since no microscopical structure details of the nucleus are considered.
The excitation energy scales inversely with the radius of the nucleus, and thus inversely with the cube root of its mass number.
The resonance width is understood in analogy to frictional damping of the collective motion.

H.~Steinwedel, J.~H.~D.~Jensen and P.~Jensen further built on this model in 1950~\cite{SteinwedelJensen1950-GDR-Hydrodynamic-Model,JensenJensen1950-GDR-Hydrodynamic-Model,SteinwedelJensenJensen1950-GDR-Hydrodynamic-Model}.
Goldhaber and Teller had effectively modeled the oscillation of two interpenetrating rigid spheres, which required an arbitrary parameter for the restoring force and changes in total nucleon density.
Steinwedel, Jensen, and Jensen, however, considered the oscillation of proton against neutron fluid within a common volume of fixed shape.
While Goldhaber and Teller had previously noted this as a potential alternative treatment, Steinwedel, Jensen and Jensen showed that, in this approach, the restoring force of the oscillation can be derived from the nuclear symmetry energy already known from the semi-empirical Bethe-WeizsÃ¤cker mass formula.

The next major step in the development of the geometrical, collective model of the \gls{gdr} was the work by M.~Danos and K.~Okamoto in 1958~\cite{Danos1958-GDR-Splitting-Model,Okamoto1958-GDR-Splitting-Model}.
They both independently concluded that the \gls{gdr} of axially deformed nuclei should split into two overlapping sub-resonances of different energies, corresponding to the oscillation modes along and perpendicular to the symmetry axis of the nucleus.
% This is due to the nuclear deformation allowing the oscillation of protons and neutrons against each other either along the nuclear symmetry axis or perpendicular to it.
% Since the axes have different lengths, the frequencies of the oscillations are different and therefore the \gls{gdr} splits into two peaks with a stronger splitting for stronger deformations.
This provided an explanation for the previously observed splitting of the \gls{gdr} in the photoabsorption cross sections of deformed nuclei compared to spherical ones.

Since then, numerous aspects of the \gls{gdr} have been studied across many nuclei, both experimentally and through macroscopic and microscopic theories.
% In particular, the photoabsorption cross section of the \gls{gdr} has been extensively measured~\cite{BermanFultz1975-GDR-CS-Measurements-Review,DietrichBerman1988-GDR-CS-Measurements-Review} throughout the entire nuclear chart.
% A bulk of these data were obtained through photoneutron measurements employing \gls{real-photon} beams.
In addition to the \gls{gdr}, several other giant resonances have been found in nuclei, such as the isoscalar giant quadrupole resonance~\cite{Harakeh2001-Book}.
Furthermore, analogues to the nuclear \gls{gdr} were identified in other multiparticle systems~\cite{Connerade1987-Book-Giant-Resonances-Other-Systems} such as atoms~\cite{Ederer1964-GDR-Analogues-Atoms,Lukirskii1964-GDR-Analogues-Atoms,Samson1966-GDR-Analogues-Atoms,Wendin1973-GDR-Analogues-Atoms,Shiner2011-GDR-Analogues-Atoms,Pabst2013-GDR-Analogues-Atoms}, metallic clusters~\cite{Heer1987-GDR-Analogues-Metallic-Clusters,Hoheisel1988-GDR-Analogues-Metallic-Clusters,Tiggesbaeumker1992-GDR-Analogues-Metallic-Clusters}, and fullerenes~\cite{Gensterblum1991-GDR-Analogues-Fullerenes,Hertel1992-GDR-Analogues-Fullerenes}.

Still, despite decades of research on the nuclear \gls{gdr}, many questions remain unanswered.
What is the true microscopic structure of the \gls{gdr}?
How do the current microscopic and macroscopic models relate to each other and its true structure?
What is its lifetime, and does it vary across the energy range of the \gls{gdr}?
What role does internal decay play compared to particle emission?
How does the decay behavior of the \gls{gdr} evolve as a function of excitation energy?
These are just a few of the unresolved questions.
To address them, more work is needed from both, the experimental and the theoretical side.
New experimental data are needed to challenge and refine current theories, ultimately deepening our understanding of the \gls{gdr} and the nucleus as a whole.
This work seeks to contribute to these efforts by developing and applying a novel method to measure the \Î³ decay of the \gls{gdr}. %, a fundamental property that so far had remained poorly characterized.


\section{Objectives and structure of this work}
\label{sec:Introduction-Objectives}
As previously stated, this work focuses on the investigation of hitherto hardly studied \Î³ decay of the \gls{gdr}.
Its goal is to establish the \Î³ decay as an experimental observable sensitive to the internal structure of the \gls{gdr} of spherical and deformed nuclei and thereby the nuclei themselves.
In particular, one of the main purposes of this work is to resolve the \Î³ decays of the \gls{gdr} to the \st2+1 and \st0+1 states at arbitrary excitation energies of the \gls{gdr} and, thus for the first time, measure their individual energy evolution in a deformed nucleus.
This will enable a long-overdue, rigorous experimental test of the geometrical model of the \gls{gdr} through its predictions on the \Î³-decay branching ratios of the \gls{gdr} to the ground-state band.

To this end, first a novel experimental approach to measure \Î³ decay of the \gls{gdr} has to be developed, surpassing the limitations of previous experiments.
This is achieved by combining the established nuclear resonance fluorescence (NRF) and photoactivation techniques with state-of-the-art \gls{lcb} photon sources in the \gls{gdr}'s energy domain.
\Gls{lcb} photon beams enable a selective and efficient photoexcitation of the \gls{gdr} within narrow, freely tunable energy regions.
Its \Î³ decay in the induced nuclear resonance fluorescence (NRF) reactions can then be measured with high resolution and statistics.
The ability to conduct such measurements at arbitrary excitation energies allows for a systematic study of this observable's evolution with energy across the entire \gls{gdr}.
To resolve \Î³ decays to final states close in energy, such as the \st2+1 and \st0+1 states of deformed nuclei where the decay signals overlap and cannot be energy-resolved, linearly polarized \gls{lcb} photon beams are utilized.
Excitation of the \gls{gdr} with linearly polarized photon beams results in distinct angular distributions of its \Î³ decays to various states, allowing for the experimental disentanglement of these overlapping signals.
% A linear polarization of the \gls{lcb} photon beams allows disentanglement of \Î³ decays to states close in energy, based on their unique angular distributions in this case, even when the decay signals overlap and cannot be energy-resolved.
Finally, simultaneous photoactivation measurements are employed to calibrate the Photon flux (photon flux), enabling the determination of absolute \Î³-decay cross sections from the \gls{nrf} data.

% Specifically, a main goal is to resolve the \Î³ decays of the \gls{gdr} to the \st2+1 and \st0+1 states and, thus for the first time, measure their individual energy evolutions in a deformed nucleus through this novel method.
The next milestone is to apply this experimental approach to study the \Î³-decay behavior of the \gls{gdr} for spherical and deformed even-even nuclei.
% Thus, experiments on the spherical \Ce and the deformed \Sm have been conducted at the \gls{higs} at the \gls{tunl} in Durham, North Carolina, USA, for the pilot study.
Thus, experiments have been conducted at the High Intensity \texorpdfstring{\ensuremath{{\symup{\gamma}}}}{γ}-ray Source (HI\texorpdfstring{\ensuremath{{\symup{\gamma}}}}{γ}S) at the Triangle Universities Nuclear Laboratory (TUNL) in Durham, North Carolina, USA.
The nuclei that have been selected for the pilot study are the deformed \Sm and the semi-magic, spherical \Ce.
Data have been collected for both rare-earth nuclei at six excitation energies, covering the full evolution of their \glspl{gdr}.
The analysis of this data to extract the \Î³-decay behavior of their \glspl{gdr} constitutes the core of this work.
Building on the success of the pilot study, a follow-up experiment has furthermore been conducted on the deformed \ce{^{232}Th} and the doubly magic, spherical \ce{^{208}Pb} extending the \gls{gdr} research campaign from the rare-earth to the actinide region of the nuclear chart.
However, the data from these experiments have yet to be analyzed and will be the subject of future studies.

Finally, the implications of the \Ce and \Sm experimental data on the nature of their \glspl{gdr} and the nuclei themselves are discussed.
In particular, the long-overdue, rigorous test of the geometrical model of the \gls{gdr} is performed by comparing the novel \gls{gdr} \Î³-decay data to the model's predictions, thus accomplishing the final objective of this work.

The subsequent chapters follow these objectives.
First, the basic physics of photonuclear reactions and their application as an experimental technique are introduced in \cref{ch:Photonuclear-Reactions}, focusing on \gls{nrf} as the photonuclear reaction most relevant to this work.
This includes a discussion of the peculiarities of performing \gls{nrf} experiments on the \gls{gdr} due to interference effects, and the predictions of the geometrical model on the \gls{gdr}'s \Î³-decay behavior.
\Cref{ch:Experiment} begins with a brief overview of the \gls{lcb} technique and the High Intensity \texorpdfstring{\ensuremath{{\symup{\gamma}}}}{γ}-ray Source (HI\texorpdfstring{\ensuremath{{\symup{\gamma}}}}{γ}S) facility implementing this technique, followed by a detailed description of the experimental approach developed to measure \Î³ decay of the \gls{gdr} via \gls{nrf} reactions induced by \gls{lcb} photon beams.
This chapter also covers the pilot experiment on \Ce and \Sm realized with this approach.
\Cref{ch:Analysis} then elaborates on the data analysis of this experiment, culminating in the extraction of the \Î³-decay branching ratios of the \glspl{gdr} of these nuclei to their \st2+1 and \st0+1 states from the measured \gls{nrf} spectra.
% as well as absolute cross sections for respective \gls{nrf} reactions on their \glspl{gdr}.
The results of this analysis on the \Î³ decay of the \Ce and \Sm \glspl{gdr} are presented in \cref{ch:Results} and discussed in \cref{ch:Discussion-and-Interpretation}.
In particular, \cref{ch:Discussion-and-Interpretation} compares the experimental results to the predictions of the geometrical model of the \gls{gdr} on its \Î³-decay behavior.
Finally, \cref{ch:Summary-and-Outlook} concludes this work with a summary and outlook.

The complete dataset and analysis codes at the core of this work are openly accessible in Ref.~\cite{Kleemann2024-154Sm-GDR-TUdatalib-Repository} via the TUdatalib repository of Technische UniversitÃ¤t Darmstadt, enabling full reproduction of all results.
Furthermore, parts of this work were published in Ref.~\cite{Kleemann2024-154Sm-GDR}.

